segments.text: I just know a lot of hours a day.

So after a lot of discussion, they did give me a few hours of credit for some of my military experience, like in the basic requirements, there was some military requirements that they'd give me credit for had I gone into ROTC, so nationally qualified.
So they did give me a few hours, but still, it was impossible for me to get, they said, a necessary number of hours for a degree in electrical engineering.
talked in terms of, well, why can't it take more of these courses?
And he said, well, you're talking in terms of 28 hours.
Well, I think I can do this.
I've got nothing else to do.
And I finally prevailed upon him to let me try it.
And we said, well, OK, we'll try this.
And I started out.
And it was, I assure you, a laborious undertaking.
extremely hard at first.
Three or four o'clock in the morning, I was still busy.

And they gave me a little bit of freedom to go in and register early in order to get the classes before they filled up at the property, to be sure I'd take advantage of the hours at a certain time of the day for a particular class that I needed to have.
So they were very, very cooperative and helpful, very understanding, and I started out.
And that's the way I went for the first year, straight through, all the year, for 12 months, summer and all.
And so at the end of 12 months, how many credits did you get?
Well, I had the equivalent of two years of credits towards an electrical engineering degree.
At the end of 12 months, you had two years.
At the end of 12 months.
And I think I'd made, well, a practice grade A. I think I'd made one B, or one B, grade A courses.
So they were...
Now, all of the people that knew me, and professors, and the heads of the various schools knew me.
They were ecstatic.
And they showed me this congratulating, encouraged me.
But the head of the School of Electrical Engineering, I forget his name right now.
It's been so long ago.
What, 40 years?
Well, almost 40 years ago.
He said, there's no way that we could continue, particularly since you start getting into lab courses,
direct current and electrical power, since A&M stressed that.
And there's just no way I'd get enough hours and couldn't possibly get a degree in two years.
So to make a long story short, I collaborated with more of the officials in school and then also my headquarters back at Terry University.
And upon a suggestion of them and giving me complete freedom, I sat down with the officials of A&M and ended up taking
orienting my work toward a degree.
And at that time, it was called management engineering, I think now called investment engineering.
And I'm delighted I did, because it gave me the opportunity to get my degree in the time allotted.
Plus, since I'd done so well, they knew I was motivated back home in their university.
They granted me another four years, one more semester.
Four months.
Four months, one more semester to get my degree.
I started in again, and the same number of hours, and at the end of two years and four months, I had gotten my degree in management engineering and graduated with honors.
I was a member of the Tau Beta Pi and National Honor Society, and I didn't participate in any other activities.
I'd have loved to have participated in football, but of course I couldn't.
the work.
I was dedicated to it and I was doing well and I was achieving my objective.
It was extremely hard on my wife, my two little girls, extremely hard.
But we got through it and of course the officials back there at the university were elated and I got high marks for my achievement in getting a degree.
And I must admit that I was very, very proud that I didn't pick A&M.
I'm still proud of it.
That's where I wanted to go when I was a kid, and then I finally achieved that objective, and I have the Air Force to thank for that.
When you were younger, you had an idea of what it would be like.
You had a perception of A&M, and then you didn't get to go to college for a decade after, or 15 years later.
In what ways was your earlier perception of A&M correct, and in which way was it incorrect?
Well, that's a good question.
I can say I was about 32 when I started in 47.
And here I was a full colonel, dedicated in having a full military career to go back to immediately when I was leaving college.
It's sort of like somebody in a corporation of business being given two years to go get a degree then come back to a job in a corporation.
I knew I had a job.
There was no reason for me not to concentrate strictly on studying.
That was my objective.
Extracurricular activities was out of the question.
I didn't have any desire to do that.
But here I was cast in that type of environment and considerably older than
You know, the other students in their late teens and a few maybe in their early 20s.

A few graduate types that I mingled with, but nobody, hardly anybody at my age level except a couple, two or three colonels, lieutenant colonels about my age in the same program from the United States Army and the United States Air Force.
I mixed easily.
with the professors in the classes.
They became very helpful and knew what I was doing, and we had a very high mutual respect for each other.
The professors never singled me out one way or the other to either discriminate or to give preference.
I guess I was another student.
The students, by far the majority of the students,
respected me and realized what I was doing.
As usual in a group of people that big, you always have some eight balls as far as I'm concerned.
I can recall two or three that taunted me.
Really?
Taunted me considerably.
Gee, I wish I had your set up, a full colonel doing a full colonel's pay and going to school.
Actually, you don't even have to study.
Two or three of the types of this nature, obviously you can imagine what type of people they were.
I doubt they even finished their studying.
And this bothered me for a while.
These were kids in the Corps?
No, not in the Corps.
They were not members of the ROTC.
They were veterans?
No, none of them were veterans.
They were just young kids.
Did you wear your uniform to class?
No, I never wore my uniform.
I, on weekends, I still had to give a flying time and maintain my flying pay and my capability to fly.
Weekend, all the pilots of the group would be about three or four of us.
Some of them were not pilots.
But we who were pilots would get in a car and drive over to Burge to Murfreespace in Austin, Texas, and fly our aircraft for, ready to fly at least four hours a month.
Generally what we would do,

be three or four of us come over and get in a transport aircraft on a Saturday afternoon and just get in the airplane and schedule hops that would take us all night long and up to about noon on Sunday, flying time, where we'd change its controls of the aircraft so that by the time all of us got back, all of us would have at least four hours in the airplane.
So it had to require at least eight to 12 hours flying time.
That's the way we'd do that.
How many hours a month did you have to have?
Four hours.
Basically four hours.
And this was still required while we were going to college.
Why didn't you wear your uniform?
They preferred we do not.
Oh, the Air Force?
It was not a regulation.
Well, almost a regulation, yes.
It was one of our guidelines.
Go in civilian clothes mixed with the student body and don't be obvious.
In other words, there was expected to be some criticism.
Maybe the Air Force would spend money sending the guys to school and they would be out training in the military.
I think this was the basis of some of the toning that I got from one or two of the kids.
How did you get along with the kids in the Corps?
Excellent.
As a matter of fact, it so happened that my brother, my youngest brother, actually I paid his way through A&M at the time.
He was in the cadet corps, and after, you know, even that first year, word got around who I was, his brother and so forth, and I got along fine.
Matter of fact, we had, you know, the air PMS&T, and many times we got together and we had dinner together and I associated with them, you know, military, professional military service.
Sometimes I even went over and gave maybe a lecture.
to some of the students at RMTC.

The one thing I observed that was very, in effect, was educational to me, really in a philosophical way, was, you know, at this time there were many veterans going to colleges, and A&M with the freedom they had, not only in education, but in
Very informal dress and all.
Veteran not having to take ROTC, of course, and many of them, and I mean hundreds of thousands of them at this time in the program.
Some married with a baby, living in trailers, actually provided trailer space on the campus back by the Kyle Field for them to live in.
These guys knew what they were going to school for.
They were, many of them were matured by, you know, combat.
Their attitude was remarkably different in college towards their education.
And, well not surprisingly, might be as you'd expect it, they were A students.
And it led me to believe that, do some soul searching about our American system of education, particularly time wise and the life of a young man.

And quite often I thought, goodness, as long as we have the draft, why not think in terms of trying to induce a young man to put a year or two of service in right after high school, and take advantage of the maturing and ripening process in military service amongst men, and then at one moment release him from the service.
let him go to college, and perhaps even help him pay part of his college.
I still think this is what he looked at.

Because so many students, and backed up by many discussions I had with the professors along these lines, just the average high school graduate that came to college just didn't know what he wanted to do.
in a lot of areas just wasn't educated well enough either to start taking up a college, like college algebra.
He couldn't take college algebra.
As a matter of fact, A&M did have refresher courses in algebra.
So it was a, I learned a lot in the field of education, if you will.
What about your professors?
Were there any that you thought, well, they were special in any way to you, that helped you in any way?
Do you remember any of them?
Oh yeah, I remember a fact that I can close my eyes and see many of them right now.
Names-wise, I can't remember all the names.
I remember Dr. Perry, the head of the School of Management Engineering, who was a very fine man and who did everything he could to anything I wanted to do within reason, he would readily approve of.
He was instrumental in granting me the authority to take so many hours.
The young fellow who was head of mechanical drawing in the freshman course, a real young fellow, he had had some military service.
He was very helpful in understanding.

All of them, without exception, were readily available to me to talk to about any particular time, particularly making adjustments or a 32-year-old man coming back to college, you know, and practically every one of them.
Well, I'd say 50% of them, maybe 70% of them, were younger than I.
My physics professor was a, I guess what you call him, a paraplegic, not a paraplegic, he was a...
relatively young man, and extremely brilliant in physics.
And remember, we busted the atom bomb.
But it had impact on the teaching of physics.
Some of the books had to be.
And they were just introducing an atomic physics course at A&M about the time I started school.
And he was a very understanding type of person.
But he was one of these spastic types that was physically very
at a terrible disadvantage, particularly writing on a wall, on a slate and chalk.
And I remember him because I felt sorry for him.
He had such a disadvantage, but yet here he was teaching students, and that gentleman finally committed suicide.
One of my statistical
data statistics course in management engineering.
That gentleman may still be at A&M.
I don't know.
I can't remember his name.
He was very helpful, a relatively young guy.
And he took special time out to help me on a new type of mathematics I'd never been concerned with, permutations and probabilities.
What do you think of the training?
I mean, the academic training that you received at A&M, do you think it was adequate?
Was it good, mediocre, average?
What do you think?
When you say academic training, you mean actually the instructing I got?
No, the quality of the instruction.
Outstanding.
Outstanding.
Outstanding.
And I can't think of a single- Did it prepare you for a career if you wanted to go into engineering management, if you want industrial engineering?
I'm glad you asked that question.

All the professors, and to a certain extent I remember students even being interested in my question, because I'd ask a question pertaining to how I visualize it in the future and applying it maybe to, let's say, strictly the military, like a course in handling people.
Industrial relations, you know, maybe I'd ask a question about the officers versus the airmen rather than management versus labor.
The professors were actually delighted with the question because it was a strange question to them.
But it was outstanding.
Now, I was wondering about some of the so-called traditions that we have at A&M and what your opinion was of them.
One is hazing.
Of course, you weren't.
in an official manner, but you must have seen some of the hazing and some of the spanking and things like that.
What was your opinion of this?
Well, remember I'd been through the Flying Cadets.
Sure.
And they had a very, very similar type of hazing program in the Flying Cadets.
In some ways, a little bit more drastic than what I observed during the time I was at A&M.
I didn't mind that.
I wasn't against it, and I don't know, I accepted it as part of the tradition of Texas A&M and as a method of seeing if the young guy, when he came to A&M, if he could take it.
And I wasn't against it.
If it's overdone, where maybe a man was physically, if you will, torture a little bit.
I also wanted to ask you now, during your years in the service, you must have met a number of West Point graduates, a number of Aggie officers, and of course, a number of Air Force Academy officers.
And I'd like you to compare the quality of a second lieutenant from each one of these institutions.
Compare them with each other.
I've thought about that a lot, and actually, when I came across various graduates, I thought of the first question a lot.
I can truthfully say I didn't see any difference.
You couldn't really tell.
Even on the second lieutenant?
No.
Even allowing for my bias towards A&M because I was making graduates, I still would say
It was equal.
You put them up one against the other, and there was really no difference.

The training at A&M, in my opinion, not having gone through Westmont, Indianapolis, or the Air Force Academy, I can't say positively, but I got the impression after talking to a lot of those boys, that it was very much the same attitude to the kids when they were going through the school.
It was very much the same.
But the product that they produced, it was about the same.
But there's no doubt in my mind that the officer that came out of Texas A&M was a very fine officer in the services.
I don't think I've ever come across an Aggie officer in the military that I found I had trouble with.
I can truthfully say that.
I can't say that.
about West Horners and getting Navy to change officers.
I have come across a few of them.
And of course, probably over the long haul, I've met more of them.
But of course, I can't ever think of an Aggie that I've come across.
Did you favor Aggies?
Were you biased toward Aggies after you went to A&M?
I mean, did you try to promote them faster because they were Aggies?
No, sirree.
Any way that you acted any different to Aggies?
No.
I very carefully watched myself on OERs when I was grading an Aggie.
If anything, I probably know the other way.
I didn't.
I never wanted to be biased toward an Aggie on his OER with respect to his career.
I'm not that type of an officer.
Now, I've often heard that A&M is
more than just an institution of higher learning, but it's something special.
Would you agree with that?

I guess I have to answer that yes, and then go back and say that that's the reason I think always, even when I was a young fella and first learned even what a college or university was, I've always wanted to go to A&M.
And I guess it's just that there was something about spirit

There was an Aggie or an A&M spirit that I learned, first heard about and learned more and more about and became exposed to it with Aggie officers, you know, even before I went to Texas A&M in a service and talking to them.
And I just thought there was something special about spirit that they had.
And I swear, I just don't think
It's hard to put your finger on it, but I don't think they have this open spirit at the academies.
I can't define it.
I think it may be that I'm trying to say it's a more enforced, therefore I must do it type of a spirit at the academies, whereas at A&M it's just sort of a self-instilled,
Traditional, if you will.
Tradition going out of what I don't know, but to me it's traditional.
It's just a spirit.
And you hear all over the United States today the Aggie spirit.
I don't know.
It's just great, and I think it still exists.
What were your feelings when you left A&M?
Well, I tell you, I was tired.
I bet you were tired.
And I was...
I had been out of my military environment, my professional military environment, for over two years.
So really, I was glad to be leaving A&M and go back to an assignment.
But I had nothing more but gratitude and thanks for everybody at the institution because I had gotten my degree, achieved my objective,
I was proud.
Also, I was particularly happy for my wife and family because I get to see them more and be part of the family again because I've been studying hard.
Oh, yeah.
Well, you were in, it looks like, a temporary assignment from July 1949 to October 1949 at Mitchell Air Force Base in New York.
Was that a temporary assignment?
Well, no, it was a...
It was an assignment oriented to air defense.
At that time, the Air Force was trying to set up a separate command structure within the Air Force itself for the specific function of the air defense role of the United States.
And they set up an organization called Continental Air Defense Command at Mitchell Air Force Base.
You remember me telling you about Bruce Holloway, who was a major over in China.
He asked for me and I wanted to go and he had followed my career at A&M and knew what I'd done.
So I ended up going up there and I worked for him in planning.
Okay.
And at that time I started
It was rather a... Until 1951 then.
Right.
And then it was time to go to an air work college.
Okay, but I want to know about this.
There's a couple of questions I want to know about the Continental Air Defense Command.
With this, of course, we were working directly with the Canadians, right?
Yes, at that time we started the planning and...
with ultimately NORAD, North American Air Defense Command, in mind.
And that's where the seeds of organization were born right there.
As a matter of fact, working for General Holloway and General Thatcher and Colonel George Brown, who incidentally eventually became the chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.
A very, very fine person.
Brilliant man.
He was assistant D.O.
under General Thatcher.
Bruce Holloway had plans, and I was his assistant in plans.
So we drew up the basic plans for coordination and planning with the Royal Canadian Air Force for eventual organization that turned out to be eventually the North American Air Defense Command.
What were the plans?
It was just integrate the two and have one Air Defense Command for the entire North American
In case of an attack.
Continent.
Including, we even had ultimate plans of turning to Mexico, but we dropped that.
Why?
Well, the primary emphasis was from the north.
Bombers coming over the North Pole, straight across from Russia to us.
And it was less of a threat, where a bomber might come around from the south, across Mexico.
And where would be, in case of an attack, thinking back to 1949,
Where would be the headquarters?
At that time- Where would you direct the defense from?
We began to do plans right then for the headquarters in Colorado, in the mountainous area, with the ultimate plan for something in the mountain, in the hole.
The current NORAD control center in
Colorado Springs, up in the mountains.
I was born in the planning hours right there at Mitchell Air Force Base.
And what did the Canadians think of having the command center in Colorado and not in Canada?
They understood it and went along with it.
Actually, they couldn't afford it anyhow.
One of the basic decisions I remember, General Holloway, at that time Colonel Holloway, he and I were sitting in a little office about
eight by eight feet, and trying to figure out, well, how are we going to get the Canadians to participate in this?
They can't afford it.
And I said, why don't we think in terms of, we'll pay two-thirds, you pay one-third.

That stuck from then on, and that was the basis for the original planning of all the pine tree air defenses, which were the first radar I put along the southern Canadian border adjacent to the United States and up the Labrador coast.
And then the due line, which eventually was put across northern Canada, they paid for one-third and they paid for two-thirds.
And that was basically your idea?
Really?
Because I've read that in documents, the one-third, two-thirds.
You have?
Yeah.
I read that in histories and I didn't know that was your basic idea.
I thought that they would have proposed that, because they didn't.
Oh, should have left it to them.
They would say, well, you pay for the whole thing.
We'll just participate.
And matter of fact, looking back now, comparing what they had and what we had, where we saw and so forth, I think it was commendable that they agreed to pay for one third of it.
Sure.
But they had a lot of other stipulations that
was to their favor much more than just dollar bills.
For instance, to build radar sites, we had to use Canadian labor and Canadian organizations, so that gave them stimulated economy and industry.
They permitted us to man certain stations.
They didn't have the manpower to do it.
Some production of radars and the gear, that kind of gear, went to radar sites.
had to be produced in Canada.
So really saying it, you know, we'd pay one-third, we'd pay two-thirds, really they got a lot more out of it than we did, but it was worth it.
And that basic type planning grew eventually what turned out to be NORAD.
And, of course, the deputy commander was a marshal, a four-star general from the Royal Canadian Air Force.
Are the British included in this?
No, no.
It's RCAM, Royal Canadian Air Force.
Tell me about the relations between the Canadian officers and the American officers.
Were there any times that there was tension?
Never.
As a matter of fact, working with the Royal Canadian Air Force types was just like working with America.
No problem, as a matter of fact.

I can't think of any problem, ever any problem, either at the planning stage and in Ottawa and Washington D.C. at the high level stages where we even sat down in some cases with, you know, political civilians, high level civilians, State Department types.
Never any.
It was, for instance, compared to the problem I had in Russia dealing with people, no problem whatsoever.
And subsequent dealings with the Italians and NATO, never.
It's just like planning with Americans.
No problem whatsoever.
And subsequently in the field when I had command of radar divisions and fighter squadrons, the corporation was splendid.
They're terrific bunch.
What about the quality of the Air Force officers?
Canada?
Great.
Terrific.
On our quality?
Oh, yeah.
Terrific.
See, they were smaller.
Sure.
And I don't know if that makes for them being as good or better, but they had the cream of the crop of Canada, young men.
And a lot of the equipment they used was our equipment and vice versa.
We had standardization parts.
We're the British, too, though.
Oh, yeah.
Oh, getting off on the British, don't get me wrong, the RAF are absolutely fantastic.
No, I meant we had standardization of the parts with the British also.
Oh, yeah, yeah, but a while ago you asked me if the RAF was involved.
Yeah, I was wondering if the RAF was involved in any way because, see, there's still a Dominion.
Okay, no.
And how about the planning?
What was your role as far as the planning of the dew line in the earlier warning systems?
The same thing.
Same thing, the birth of all of that North American planning was done right there by our outfit.
And the basic, and even what turned out to be the SAGE system, semi-automatic ground environment system, the computerized control of air defense.
We started the basic concept of that.
Now, what was the basic concept of that?
Air defense controlled by computer.
Oh, the SAGE.

SAGE, S-A-G-E, standing for Semi-Automatic Ground Environment System, where a controller at a normal radar site looking at the scope and seeing the blips of an incoming bomber would speak over a ground-to-air communication radio telephone, RT,
and direct a pilot across the scope, seeing him pit-blip also where he'd make the intercept.

Semi-automatic ground environment was of a nature where eventually we didn't even plan to have data link and actually tied into the flight control system of the airplane where a man wasn't even in the link.
Everything was done automatically by computer until the two blips came together on a scope.
It's automatically telling the fire control system and the all-weather fighter when to fire the missile.
That was the ultimate.
In some cases, we achieved that.
In other cases... By what year?
NORAD was the last...
The...
When I took over the 25th Air Division in Tacoma, Washington at McCord Air Force Base in 1957, I believe, I took over command of what we call the grease pencil manual stage.
And it was just ready to convert into and move into this huge 50 by 50 by
50-foot-high concrete sage direction center, which occupied, which I mean, which encompassed primarily the huge computer, which incidentally was operated with electron tubes and vacuum tubes.
And it took that big a building, completely air conditioned, just to maintain that computer.
And as a side remark, can you imagine that big a
space for a computer, which now, today, in 1981, a computer does have about the size of this desk for each floor.
But in those days, as part of the system, I know I'm rambling here, but there was not enough computer programmers in the United States to do this job.
We had to hold up the program for
converting to a semi-automatic ground environment system for the United States and Canada.

We had to hold up the system for several months to actually give SDC, I forget even what that stands for out in Santa Monica, California, a contract for recruiting and training computer programmers to do this job.
It was that, and of course it was programmed to cost billions of dollars, and this is what scared
a lot of people, including people in the Air Force.
This cost would cut into, let's say, more higher priority programs like building up the Strategic Air Command Bomber Force.
And what about SAGE?
When was it activated?
The first ground, the first direction center
I believe it was the 26th Area Division just north of New York City, north of Mitchell Field, you know, where we did the initial planning.
I forget the name of it, but that was where the first Direction Center went in, and I don't remember, Terry, it had to be, when I came back to ADC and Con Ed in Northern Pittsburgh, it had to be
Around 52 or 53.
Some were in the early 50s.

Because when I went to 25th Air Division in 57, I believe, 56, 57 up at Tacoma, Washington, as 25th Air Division commander, they were just completing at Sayles Direction Center, and I moved into it before I left there within one year.
And it was probably the second or third one.
Now, ultimately, they were going to have the initial plan called for 20 of these, all of the United States.
So you can see where the cost went up.
Sure.
And eventually, we included, I believe, three in Canada.
That system, by the way, is still operating.
It's still operating.
But not in its entirety.
They have cut out a lot of them.
Sure, better radar.
Well, plus the fact that the threat of a bomber threat is just not what it used to be.
This is not, the SAGE will not take care of the missile threat.
No.
Total integration of the two air forces, Canadian and American.
Like I say, we included two direction centers across the border, one just north of Idaho and one out towards Vancouver, and those are the main ones.
of the United States.
For instance, the Detroit area lapped way over into, at least covered the populated area of southern Canada.
The air defenses of Canada and the United States were completely integrated, very smoothly done.
Still are?
Still are, including the dew line.
As you know, the dew line was practically manned by civilians.
And I was wondering if the dew line is still functional today.
Are we still using that?
I can't answer that question.
I doubt it.
But I do know that the huge radars at Thule in Alaska oriented toward the missile threat.
And I did a subsequent assignment to put in the air defenses at Thule Greenland.
Radar .
But that's later on in my career.
This sounds like a very important assignment.
It was at that time.
Looking back now, I didn't realize it.
But it was the basis for very close coordination and cooperation with another nation.
And again, I learned a lot.
This is tantamount to what you call combined planning between nations.
Combined Chiefs of Staff?
Right.
Did you do any work for the Combined Chiefs?
Oh, yeah.
Well, Canada, RCIA.
And a lot of times the Canadian Army was involved, just like the United States Army with their Nike missiles.
Sure.
Did you think it was a good idea, depending so much on a foreign nation, for our air defense system?
No.
It was so logical
And we thought of Canada so much as our buddies and friends, you know, that this never entered our mind.
The fact that they were a different nation never really entered our mind.
Not Canada, no, sir.
They felt the same way.
Well, I wonder what your feelings were during the Vietnam War when Canada, for a few years, was harboring American...
dissidents and deserters of the American military?
Did your ideas toward Canada change?
No, sir.
As a matter of fact, I didn't blame this on Canada.
It was the individuals themselves taking advantage of what were legal rights of people going to other nations and all, and I didn't blame Canada for this.
Okay.
Now, let's leave and talk about the Air Work Comp.
What was the Air War College Institute?
This was back right after the war was over.
They began to establish and think in terms of training and education then, and orienting themselves to terrific demobilization and just getting rid of all the experience they have.
And they could foresee bringing in new people and training and educating them.
And they saw the benefits and advantages
educated people, in particular in the latest tactics and strategy that we had learned, you know, in this tremendous worldwide war, World War II.
And they wanted to be able to teach this to the new incoming young people.
And so it was shortly after the war, in the early, mid and late 40s, that they began to plan for this.

It was also a feather in the cap of a young, ambitious officer to be chosen to go to these schools, because if you were chosen to go to the school and you had this on your record, then you felt that you were in towards promotion and being, you know, like you go from squadron officer school to the staff course, then to the, eventually to the Air War College, and then even eventually, well, that to the National War College, which was a joint school in Washington, D.C.
So I was delighted, and as a matter of fact, I wanted to go.
I remember doing some soul searching, and I think all of us did that.
Is this really the best route to take to spend a year in a school and miss some command opportunities for, let's say, some newly formed jet organizations, fighter organizations?
You ask yourself that question a lot of times,
I finally decided, and talked to a lot of my senior officers, the commander, that it was best to go to the Air Force.
So I went, gladly.
And what about your curriculum?
It was a combination of what it was, really it covered the waterfront, politics to economics

to psychological, to actual military problems and principles, the principles of war, how the growing, and particularly taken from the lesson of World War II, how nations depend on one another, combined planning, joint planning, alliances, and then right on down to tactics and technique of operating the advanced equipment
the problems of training.
It covered the waterfront, just about.
Well, it provided a field grade type officer, meaning major, lieutenant, colonel, colonel.
It provided him with a good understanding of command type problems he'd be confronted with in his later years, let's say as a general officer.
It was really worthwhile, a terrific idea, and I think there's still great school.
